# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: actin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:actin/3-utr] In molecular genetics, the **three prime untranslated region** (**3′ UTR**) is the section of messenger RNA (mRNA) that immediately follows the translation termination codon.
[src:actin/3-utr] The 3′ UTR often contains regulatory regions that post-transcriptionally influence gene expression.
[src:actin/3-utr] During gene expression, an mRNA molecule is transcribed from the DNA sequence and is later translated into a protein.
[src:actin/3-utr] Several regions of the mRNA molecule are not translated into a protein including the 5′ cap, 5′ untranslated region, 3′ untranslated region and poly(A) tail.
[src:actin/3-utr] Regulatory regions within the 3′ untranslated region can influence polyadenylation, translation efficiency, localization, and stability of the mRNA.
[src:actin/3-utr] The 3′ UTR contains binding sites for both regulatory proteins and microRNAs (miRNAs).
[src:actin/3-utr] By binding to specific sites within the 3′ UTR, miRNAs can decrease gene expression of various mRNAs by either inhibiting translation or directly causing degradation of the transcript.
[src:actin/3-utr] The 3′ UTR also has silencer regions which bind to repressor proteins and will inhibit the expression of the mRNA.
[src:actin/3-utr] Many 3′ UTRs also contain AU-rich elements (AREs).
[src:actin/3-utr] Proteins bind AREs to affect the stability or decay rate of transcripts in a localized manner or affect translation initiation.
[src:actin/3-utr] Furthermore, the 3′ UTR contains the sequence AAUAAA that directs addition of several hundred adenine residues called the poly(A) tail to the end of the mRNA transcript.
[src:actin/3-utr] Poly(A) binding protein (PABP) binds to this tail, contributing to regulation of mRNA translation, stability, and export.
[src:actin/3-utr] For example, poly(A) tail bound PABP interacts with proteins associated with the 5′ end of the transcript, causing a circularization of the mRNA that promotes translation.
[src:actin/3-utr] The 3′ UTR can also contain sequences that attract proteins to associate the mRNA with the cytoskeleton, transport it to or from the cell nucleus, or perform other types of localization.
[src:actin/3-utr] In addition to sequences within the 3′ UTR, the physical characteristics of the region, including its length and secondary structure, contribute to translation regulation.
[src:actin/3-utr] These diverse mechanisms of gene regulation ensure that the correct genes are expressed in the correct cells at the appropriate times.
[src:actin/3-utr] The 3′ UTR of mRNA has a great variety of regulatory functions that are controlled by the physical characteristics of the region.
[src:actin/3-utr] One such characteristic is the length of the 3′ UTR, which in the mammalian genome has considerable variation.
[src:actin/3-utr] This region of the mRNA transcript can range from 60 nucleotides to about 4000.
[src:actin/3-utr] On average the length for the 3′ UTR in humans is approximately 800 nucleotides, while the average length of 5′ UTRs is only about 200 nucleotides.
[src:actin/3-utr] The length of the 3′ UTR is significant since longer 3′ UTRs are associated with lower levels of gene expression.
[src:actin/3-utr] One possible explanation for this phenomenon is that longer regions have a higher probability of possessing more miRNA binding sites that have the ability to inhibit translation.
[src:actin/3-utr] In addition to length, the nucleotide composition also differs significantly between the 5′ and the 3′ UTR.
[src:actin/3-utr] The mean G+C percentage of the 5′ UTR in warm-blooded vertebrates is about 60% as compared to only 45% for 3′ UTRs.
[src:actin/3-utr] This is important because an inverse correlation has been observed between the G+C% of 5′ and 3′ UTRs and their corresponding lengths.
[src:actin/3-utr] The UTRs that are GC-poor tend to be longer than those located in GC-rich genomic regions.
[src:actin/3-utr] Sequences within the 3′ UTR also have the ability to degrade or stabilize the mRNA transcript.
[src:actin/3-utr] Modifications that control a transcript's stability allow expression of a gene to be rapidly controlled without altering translation rates.
[src:actin/3-utr] One group of elements in the 3′ UTR that can help destabilize an mRNA transcript are the AU-rich elements (AREs).
[src:actin/3-utr] These elements range in size from 50 to 150 base pairs and generally contain multiple copies of the pentanucleotide AUUUA.
[src:actin/3-utr] Early studies indicated that AREs can vary in sequence and fall into three main classes that differ in the number and arrangement of motifs.
[src:actin/3-utr] Another set of elements that is present in both the 5′ and the 3′ UTR are iron response elements (IREs).
[src:actin/3-utr] The IRE is a stem-loop structure within the untranslated regions of mRNAs that encode proteins involved in cellular iron metabolism.
[src:actin/3-utr] The mRNA transcript containing this element is either degraded or stabilized depending upon the binding of specific proteins and the intracellular iron concentrations.
[src:actin/3-utr] The 3′ UTR also contains sequences that signal additions to be made, either to the transcript itself or to the product of translation.
[src:actin/3-utr] For example, there are two different polyadenylation signals present within the 3′ UTR that signal the addition of the poly(A) tail.
[src:actin/3-utr] These signals initiate the synthesis of the poly(A) tail at a defined length of about 250 base pairs.
[src:actin/3-utr] The primary signal used is the nuclear polyadenylation signal (PAS) with the sequence AAUAAA located toward the end of the 3′ UTR.
[src:actin/3-utr] However, during early development cytoplasmic polyadenylation can occur instead and regulate the translational activation of maternal mRNAs.
[src:actin/3-utr] The element that controls this process is called the CPE which is AU-rich and located in the 3′ UTR as well.
[src:actin/3-utr] The CPE generally has the structure UUUUUUAU and is usually within 100 base pairs of the nuclear PAS.
[src:actin/3-utr] Another specific addition signaled by the 3′ UTR is the incorporation of selenocysteine at UGA codons of mRNAs encoding selenoproteins.
[src:actin/3-utr] Normally the UGA codon encodes for a stop of translation, but in this case a conserved stem-loop structure called the selenocysteine insertion sequence (SECIS) causes for the insertion of selenocysteine instead.
[src:actin/3-utr] The 3′ untranslated region plays a crucial role in gene expression by influencing the localization, stability, export, and translation efficiency of an mRNA.
[src:actin/3-utr] It contains various sequences that are involved in gene expression, including microRNA response elements (MREs), AU-rich elements (AREs), and the poly(A) tail.
[src:actin/3-utr] In addition, the structural characteristics of the 3′ UTR as well as its use of alternative polyadenylation play a role in gene expression.
[src:actin/3-utr] The 3′ UTR often contains microRNA response elements (MREs), which are sequences to which miRNAs bind. miRNAs are short, non-coding RNA molecules capable of binding to mRNA transcripts and regulating their expression.
[src:actin/3-utr] One miRNA mechanism involves partial base pairing of the 5′ seed sequence of an miRNA to an MRE within the 3′ UTR of an mRNA; this binding then causes translational repression.
[src:actin/3-utr] In addition to containing MREs, the 3′ UTR also often contains AU-rich elements (AREs), which are 50 to 150 bp in length and usually include many copies of the sequence AUUUA.
[src:actin/3-utr] ARE binding proteins (ARE-BPs) bind to AU-rich elements in a manner that is dependent upon tissue type, cell type, timing, cellular localization, and environment.
[src:actin/3-utr] In response to different intracellular and extracellular signals, ARE-BPs can promote mRNA decay, affect mRNA stability, or activate translation.
[src:actin/3-utr] This mechanism of gene regulation is involved in cell growth, cellular differentiation, and adaptation to external stimuli.
[src:actin/3-utr] It therefore acts on transcripts encoding cytokines, growth factors, tumor suppressors, proto-oncogenes, cyclins, enzymes, transcription factors, receptors, and membrane proteins.
[src:actin/3-utr] The poly(A) tail contains binding sites for poly(A) binding proteins (PABPs).
[src:actin/3-utr] These proteins cooperate with other factors to affect the export, stability, decay, and translation of an mRNA.
[src:actin/3-utr] PABPs bound to the poly(A) tail may also interact with proteins, such as translation initiation factors, that are bound to the 5′ cap of the mRNA.
[src:actin/3-utr] This interaction causes circularization of the transcript, which subsequently promotes translation initiation.
[src:actin/3-utr] Furthermore, it allows for efficient translation by causing recycling of ribosomes.
[src:actin/3-utr] While the presence of a poly(A) tail usually aids in triggering translation, the absence or removal of one often leads to exonuclease-mediated degradation of the mRNA.
[src:actin/3-utr] Polyadenylation itself is regulated by sequences within the 3′ UTR of the transcript.
[src:actin/3-utr] These sequences include cytoplasmic polyadenylation elements (CPEs), which are uridine-rich sequences that contribute to both polyadenylation activation and repression.
[src:actin/3-utr] CPE-binding protein (CPEB) binds to CPEs in conjunction with a variety of other proteins in order to elicit different responses.
[src:actin/3-utr] While the sequence that constitutes the 3′ UTR contributes greatly to gene expression, the structural characteristics of the 3′ UTR also play a large role.
[src:actin/3-utr] In general, longer 3′ UTRs correspond to lower expression rates since they often contain more miRNA and protein binding sites that are involved in inhibiting translation.
[src:actin/3-utr] Human transcripts possess 3′ UTRs that are on average twice as long as other mammalian 3′ UTRs.
[src:actin/3-utr] This trend reflects the high level of complexity involved in human gene regulation.
[src:actin/3-utr] In addition to length, the secondary structure of the 3′ untranslated region also has regulatory functions.
[src:actin/3-utr] Protein factors can either aid or disrupt folding of the region into various secondary structures.
[src:actin/3-utr] The most common structure is a stem-loop, which provides a scaffold for RNA binding proteins and non-coding RNAs that influence expression of the transcript.
[src:actin/3-utr] Another mechanism involving the structure of the 3′ UTR is called alternative polyadenylation (APA), which results in mRNA isoforms that differ only in their 3′ UTRs.
[src:actin/3-utr] This mechanism is especially useful for complex organisms as it provides a means of expressing the same protein but in varying amounts and locations.
[src:actin/3-utr] It is utilized by about half of human genes.
[src:actin/3-utr] APA can result from the presence of multiple polyadenylation sites or mutually exclusive terminal exons.
[src:actin/3-utr] Since it can affect the presence of protein and miRNA binding sites, APA can cause differential expression of mRNA transcripts by influencing their stability, export to the cytoplasm, and translation efficiency.
[src:actin/3-utr] Scientists use a number of methods to study the complex structures and functions of the 3′ UTR.
[src:actin/3-utr] Even if a given 3′ UTR in an mRNA is shown to be present in a tissue, the effects of localization, functional half-life, translational efficiency, and trans-acting elements must be determined to understand the 3′ UTR's full functionality.
[src:actin/3-utr] Computational approaches, primarily by sequence analysis, have shown the existence of AREs in approximately 5 to 8% of human 3′ UTRs and the presence of one or more miRNA targets in as many as 60% or more of human 3′ UTRs.
[src:actin/3-utr] Software can rapidly compare millions of sequences at once to find similarities between various 3′ UTRs within the genome.
[src:actin/3-utr] Experimental approaches have been used to define sequences that associate with specific RNA-binding proteins; specifically, recent improvements in sequencing and cross-linking techniques have enabled fine mapping of protein binding sites within the transcript.
[src:actin/3-utr] Induced site-specific mutations, for example those that affect the termination codon, polyadenylation signal, or secondary structure of the 3′ UTR, can show how mutated regions can cause translation deregulation and disease.
[src:actin/3-utr] These types of transcript-wide methods should help our understanding of known cis elements and trans-regulatory factors within 3′ UTRs.
[src:actin/3-utr] 3′ UTR mutations can be very consequential because one alteration can be responsible for the altered expression of many genes.
[src:actin/3-utr] Transcriptionally, a mutation may affect only the allele and genes that are physically linked.
[src:actin/3-utr] However, since 3′ UTR binding proteins also function in the processing and nuclear export of mRNA, a mutation can also affect other unrelated genes.
[src:actin/3-utr] Dysregulation of ARE-binding proteins (AUBPs) due to mutations in AU-rich regions can lead to diseases including tumorigenesis (cancer), hematopoietic malignancies, leukemogenesis, and developmental delay/autism spectrum disorders.
[src:actin/3-utr] An expanded number of trinucleotide (CTG) repeats in the 3′ UTR of the dystrophia myotonica protein kinase (DMPK) gene causes myotonic dystrophy.
[src:actin/3-utr] Retro-transposal 3-kilobase insertion of tandem repeat sequences within the 3′ UTR of fukutin protein is linked to Fukuyama-type congenital muscular dystrophy.
[src:actin/3-utr] Elements in the 3′ UTR have also been linked to human acute myeloid leukemia, alpha-thalassemia, neuroblastoma, Keratinopathy, Aniridia, IPEX syndrome, and congenital heart defects.
[src:actin/3-utr] The few UTR-mediated diseases identified only hint at the countless links yet to be discovered.
[src:actin/3-utr] Despite current understanding of 3′ UTRs, they are still relative mysteries.
[src:actin/3-utr] Since mRNAs usually contain several overlapping control elements, it is often difficult to specify the identity and function of each 3′ UTR element, let alone the regulatory factors that may bind at these sites.
[src:actin/3-utr] Additionally, each 3′ UTR contains many alternative AU-rich elements and polyadenylation signals.
[src:actin/3-utr] These cis- and trans-acting elements, along with miRNAs, offer a virtually limitless range of control possibilities within a single mRNA.
[src:actin/3-utr] Future research through the increased use of deep-sequencing based ribosome profiling will reveal more regulatory subtleties as well as new control elements and AUBPs.
[src:actin/5-utr] The **five prime untranslated region** **(5′ UTR)**, or **leader sequence**, **transcript leader**, or **leader RNA**, is the region of a messenger RNA (mRNA) that is directly upstream from the initiation codon.
[src:actin/5-utr] This region is important for the regulation of translation of a transcript by differing mechanisms in viruses, prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:actin/5-utr] Despite its name, the 5′ UTR, or a portion of it, is sometimes translated into a protein product.
[src:actin/5-utr] This product may involve in regulation of transcription, and translation of the main coding sequence of the mRNA, such as the sex-lethal gene in *Drosophila*.
[src:actin/5-utr] Regulatory elements within 5′ UTRs have also been linked to mRNA export.
[src:actin/5-utr] In many organisms, however, the 5′ UTR is completely untranslated, instead forming a complex secondary structure to regulate translation.
[src:actin/5-utr] The 5′ UTR begins at the transcription start site and ends one nucleotide before the initiation sequence (usually AUG) of the coding region.
[src:actin/5-utr] In prokaryotes, the length of the 5′ UTR tends to be 3–10 nucleotides long, while in eukaryotes it tends to be anywhere from 100 to several thousand nucleotides long.
[src:actin/5-utr] For example, the *ste11* transcript in *Schizosaccharomyces pombe* has a 2273 nucleotide 5′ UTR while the *lac* operon in *Escherichia coli* only has seven nucleotides in its 5′ UTR.
[src:actin/5-utr] The differing sizes are likely due to the complexity of the eukaryotic regulation which the 5′ UTR holds as well as the larger pre-initiation complex that must form to begin translation.
[src:actin/5-utr] The 5′ UTR can also be completely missing, in the case of **leaderless mRNAs**.
[src:actin/5-utr] Ribosomes of all three domains of life accept and translate such mRNAs.
[src:actin/5-utr] Such sequences are naturally found in all three domains of life.
[src:actin/5-utr] Humans have many pressure-related genes under a 2–3 nucleotide leader.
[src:actin/5-utr] Mammals also have other types of ultra-short leaders like the TISU sequence.
[src:actin/5-utr] The elements of a eukaryotic and prokaryotic 5′ UTR differ greatly.
[src:actin/5-utr] The prokaryotic 5′ UTR contains a ribosome binding site (RBS), also known as the Shine–Dalgarno sequence (AGGAGGU), which is usually 3–10 base pairs upstream from the initiation codon.
[src:actin/5-utr] In contrast, the eukaryotic 5′ UTR contains the Kozak consensus sequence (ACCAUGG), which contains the initiation codon.
[src:actin/5-utr] The eukaryotic 5′ UTR also contains *cis*-acting regulatory elements called upstream open reading frames (uORFs) and upstream AUGs (uAUGs) and termination codons, which have a great impact on the regulation of translation (see below).
[src:actin/5-utr] Unlike prokaryotes, 5′ UTRs can harbor introns in eukaryotes.
[src:actin/5-utr] In humans, ~35% of all genes harbor introns within the 5′ UTR.
[src:actin/5-utr] As the 5′ UTR has high GC content, secondary structures often occur within it.
[src:actin/5-utr] Hairpin loops are one such secondary structure that can be located within the 5′ UTR.
[src:actin/5-utr] These secondary structures also impact the regulation of translation.
[src:actin/5-utr] In bacteria, the initiation of translation occurs when IF-3, along with the 30S ribosomal subunit, bind to the Shine–Dalgarno (SD) sequence of the 5′ UTR.
[src:actin/5-utr] This then recruits many other proteins, such as the 50S ribosomal subunit, which allows for translation to begin.
[src:actin/5-utr] Each of these steps regulates the initiation of translation.
[src:actin/5-utr] Initiation in Archaea is less understood.
[src:actin/5-utr] SD sequences are much rarer, and the initiation factors have more in common with eukaryotic ones.
[src:actin/5-utr] In both domains, genes without Shine–Dalgarno sequences are also translated in a less understood manner.
[src:actin/5-utr] A requirement seems to be a lack of secondary structure near the initiation codon.
[src:actin/5-utr] The regulation of translation in eukaryotes is more complex than in prokaryotes.
[src:actin/5-utr] Initially, the eIF4F complex is recruited to the 5′ cap, which in turn recruits the ribosomal complex to the 5′ UTR.
[src:actin/5-utr] Both eIF4E and eIF4G bind the 5′ UTR, which limits the rate at which translational initiation can occur.
[src:actin/5-utr] However, this is not the only regulatory step of translation that involves the 5′ UTR.
[src:actin/5-utr] RNA-binding proteins sometimes serve to prevent the pre-initiation complex from forming.
[src:actin/5-utr] An example is regulation of the *msl2* gene.
[src:actin/5-utr] The protein SXL attaches to an intron segment located within the 5′ UTR segment of the primary transcript, which leads to the inclusion of the intron after processing.
[src:actin/5-utr] This sequence allows the recruitment of proteins that bind simultaneously to both the 5′ and 3′ UTR, not allowing translation proteins to assemble.
[src:actin/5-utr] However, it has also been noted that SXL can also repress translation of RNAs that do not contain a poly(A) tail, or more generally, 3′ UTR.
[src:actin/5-utr] Another important regulator of translation is the interaction between 3′ UTR and the 5′ UTR.
[src:actin/5-utr] The closed-loop structure inhibits translation.
[src:actin/5-utr] This has been observed in *Xenopus laevis*, in which eIF4E bound to the 5′ cap interacts with Maskin bound to CPEB on the 3′ UTR, creating translationally inactive transcripts.
[src:actin/5-utr] This translational inhibition is lifted once CPEB is phosphorylated, displacing the Maskin binding site, allowing for the polymerization of the PolyA tail, which can recruit the translational machinery by means of PABP.
[src:actin/5-utr] However, this mechanism has been under great scrutiny.
[src:actin/5-utr] Iron levels in cells are maintained by translation regulation of many proteins involved in iron storage and metabolism.
[src:actin/5-utr] The 5′ UTR has the ability to form a hairpin loop secondary structure (known as the iron response element or IRE) that is recognized by iron-regulatory proteins (IRP1 and IRP2).
[src:actin/5-utr] In low levels of iron, the ORF of the target mRNA is blocked as a result of steric hindrance from the binding of IRP1 and IRP2 to the IRE.
[src:actin/5-utr] When iron is high, then the two iron-regulatory proteins do not bind as strongly and allow proteins to be expressed that have a role in iron concentration control.
[src:actin/5-utr] This function has gained some interest after it was revealed that the translation of amyloid precursor protein may be disrupted due to a single-nucleotide polymorphism to the IRE found in the 5′ UTR of its mRNA, leading to a spontaneous increased risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:actin/5-utr] Another form of translational regulation in eukaryotes comes from unique elements on the 5′ UTR called upstream open reading frames (uORF).
[src:actin/5-utr] These elements are fairly common, occurring in 35–49% of all human genes.
[src:actin/5-utr] A uORF is a coding sequence located in the 5′ UTR located upstream of the coding sequences initiation site.
[src:actin/5-utr] These uORFs contain their own initiation codon, known as an upstream AUG (uAUG).
[src:actin/5-utr] This codon can be scanned for by ribosomes and then translated to create a product, which can regulate the translation of the main protein coding sequence or other uORFs that may exist on the same transcript.
[src:actin/5-utr] The translation of the protein within the main ORF after a uORF sequence has been translated is known as reinitiation.
[src:actin/5-utr] The process of reinitiation is known to reduce the translation of the ORF protein.
[src:actin/5-utr] Control of protein regulation is determined by the distance between the uORF and the first codon in the main ORF.
[src:actin/5-utr] A uORF has been found to increase reinitiation with the longer distance between its uAUG and the start codon of the main ORF, which indicates that the ribosome needs to reacquire translation factors before it can carry out translation of the main protein.
[src:actin/5-utr] For example, *ATF4* regulation is performed by two uORFs further upstream, named uORF1 and uORF2, which contain three amino acids and fifty-nine amino acids, respectively.
[src:actin/5-utr] The location of uORF2 overlaps with the *ATF4* ORF.
[src:actin/5-utr] During normal conditions, the uORF1 is translated, and then translation of uORF2 occurs only after eIF2-TC has been reacquired.
[src:actin/5-utr] Translation of the uORF2 requires that the ribosomes pass by the *ATF4* ORF, whose start codon is located within uORF2.
[src:actin/5-utr] However, during stress conditions, the 40S ribosome will bypass uORF2 because of a decrease in concentration of eIF2-TC, which means the ribosome does not acquire one in time to translate uORF2.
[src:actin/5-utr] Viral (as well as some eukaryotic) 5′ UTRs contain internal ribosome entry sites, which is a cap-independent method of translational activation.
[src:actin/5-utr] Instead of building up a complex at the 5′ cap, the IRES allows for direct binding of the ribosomal complexes to the transcript to begin translation.
[src:actin/5-utr] The IRES enables the viral transcript to translate more efficiently due to the lack of needing a preinitiation complex, allowing the virus to replicate quickly.
[src:actin/5-utr] Transcription of the *msl-2* transcript is regulated by multiple binding sites for fly *Sxl* at the 5′ UTR.
[src:actin/5-utr] In particular, these poly-uracil sites are located close to a small intron that is spliced in males, but kept in females through splicing inhibition.
[src:actin/5-utr] This splicing inhibition is maintained by *Sxl*.
[src:actin/5-utr] When present, *Sxl* will repress the translation of *msl2* by increasing translation of a start codon located in a uORF in the 5′ UTR (see above for more information on uORFs).
[src:actin/5-utr] Also, *Sxl* outcompetes TIA-1 to a poly(U) region and prevents snRNP (a step in alternative splicing) recruitment to the 5′ splice site.
[src:actin/acta1] Actin alpha 1 which is expressed in skeletal muscle is one of six different actin isoforms which have been identified.
[src:actin/acta1] Actins are highly conserved proteins that are involved in cell motility, structure and integrity.
[src:actin/acta1] Alpha actins are a major constituent of the contractile apparatus.
[src:actin/acta1] Skeletal alpha actin expression is induced by stimuli and conditions known to cause muscle formation.
[src:actin/acta1] Such conditions result in fusion of committed cells (satellite cells) into myotubes, to form muscle fibers.
[src:actin/acta1] Skeletal actin itself, when expressed, causes expression of several other "myogenic genes", which are essential to muscle formation.
[src:actin/acta1] One key transcription factor that activates skeletal actin gene expression is Serum Response Factor ("SRF"), a protein that binds to specific sites on the promoter DNA of the actin gene.
[src:actin/acta1] SRF may bring a number of other proteins to the promoter of skeletal actin, such as androgen receptor, and thereby contribute to induction of skeletal actin gene expression by androgenic (often termed "anabolic") steroids.
[src:actin/acta1] Actin, alpha 1 has been shown to interact with TMSB4X, MIB2 and PRKCE.
[src:actin/acta2] In humans, ACTA2 is encoded by the *ACTA2* gene located on 10q22-q24.
[src:actin/acta2] Mutations in this gene cause a variety of vascular diseases, such as thoracic aortic disease, coronary artery disease, stroke, Moyamoya disease, and multisystemic smooth muscle dysfunction syndrome.
[src:actin/acta2] ACTA2 (commonly referred to as alpha-smooth muscle actin or α-SMA) is often used as a marker of myofibroblast formation.
[src:actin/acta2] Studies have shown that ACTA2 is associated with TGF-β pathway that enhances contractile properties of hepatic stellate cells leading to liver fibrosis and cirrhosis.
[src:actin/actb] Actin beta has been shown to interact with SPTBN2.
[src:actin/actb] In addition, RNA-binding protein Sam68 was found to interact with the mRNA encoding actin beta, which regulates the synaptic formation of the dendritic spines with its cytoskeletal components.
[src:actin/actb] Actin beta has been shown to activate eNOS, thereby increasing NO production.
[src:actin/actb] An eight-amino acid motif (326-333) in eNOS has been shown to mediate the interaction between actin and eNOS.
[src:actin/actb] Recurrent mutations in this gene have been associated to cases of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma.
[src:actin/actb] De novo gain-of-function mutations in this gene is associated with Baraitser-Winter syndrome.
[src:actin/actb] Actin beta is often used in Western blotting as a loading control, to normalize total protein amounts and check for eventual protein degradation in the samples.
[src:actin/actb] Its transcript is also commonly used as a housekeeping gene standard in qPCR.
[src:actin/actb] Its molecular weight is approximately 42 kDa.
[src:actin/actc1] Cardiac alpha actin is a 42.0 kDa protein composed of 377 amino acids.
[src:actin/actc1] Cardiac alpha actin is a filamentous protein extending from a complex mesh with cardiac alpha-actinin (ACTN2) at Z-lines towards the center of the sarcomere.
[src:actin/actc1] Polymerization of globular actin (G-actin) leads to a structural filament (F-actin) in the form of a two-stranded helix.
[src:actin/actc1] The atomic structure of monomeric actin was solved by Kabsch et al., and closely thereafter this same group published the structure of the actin filament.
[src:actin/actc1] Actins are highly conserved proteins; the alpha actins are found in muscle tissues and are a major constituent of the contractile apparatus.
[src:actin/actc1] Cardiac (ACTC1) and skeletal (ACTA1) alpha actins differ by only four amino acids (Asp4Glu, Glu5Asp, Leu301Met, Ser360Thr; cardiac/skeletal).
[src:actin/actc1] The actin monomer has two asymmetric domains; the larger inner domain comprised by sub-domains 3 and 4, and the smaller outer domain by sub-domains 1 and 2.
[src:actin/actc1] Both the amino and carboxy-termini lie in sub-domain 1 of the outer domain.
[src:actin/actc1] Actin is a dynamic structure that can adapt two states of flexibility, with the greatest difference between the states occurring as a result of movement within sub-domain 2.
[src:actin/actc1] Myosin binding increases the flexibility of actin, and cross-linking studies have shown that myosin subfragment-1 binds to actin amino acid residues 48-67 within actin sub-domain 2, which may account for this effect.
[src:actin/actc1] It has been suggested that the *ACTC1* gene has a role during development.
[src:actin/actc1] Experiments in chick embryos found an association between *ACTC1* knockdown and a reduction in the atrial septa.
[src:actin/actc1] Polymorphisms in *ACTC1* have been linked to dilated cardiomyopathy in a small number of Japanese patients.
[src:actin/actc1] Further studies in patients from South Africa found no association.
[src:actin/actc1] The E101K missense mutation has been associated with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and left ventricular noncompaction.
[src:actin/actc1] Another mutation has in the *ACTC1* gene has been associated with atrial septal defects.
[src:actin/actg1] Human gamma-actin is 41.8 kDa in molecular weight and 375 amino acids in length.
[src:actin/actg1] Actins are highly conserved proteins that are involved in various types of cell motility, and maintenance of the cytoskeleton.
[src:actin/actg1] In vertebrates, three main groups of actin paralogs, alpha, beta, and gamma, have been identified.
[src:actin/actg1] The alpha actins are found in muscle tissues and are a major constituent of the sarcomere contractile apparatus.
[src:actin/actg1] The beta and gamma actins co-exist in most cell types as components of the cytoskeleton, and as mediators of internal cell motility.
[src:actin/actg1] Actin, gamma 1, encoded by this gene, is found in non-muscle cells in the cytoplasm, and in muscle cells at costamere structures, or transverse points of cell-cell adhesion that run perpendicular to the long axis of myocytes.
[src:actin/actg1] In myocytes, sarcomeres adhere to the sarcolemma via costameres, which align at Z-discs and M-lines.
[src:actin/actg1] The two primary cytoskeletal components of costameres are desmin intermediate filaments and gamma-actin microfilaments.
[src:actin/actg1] It has been shown that gamma-actin interacting with another costameric protein dystrophin is critical for costameres forming mechanically strong links between the cytoskeleton and the sarcolemmal membrane.
[src:actin/actg1] Additional studies have shown that gamma-actin colocalizes with alpha-actinin and GFP-labeled gamma actin localized to Z-discs, whereas GFP-alpha-actin localized to pointed ends of thin filaments, indicating that gamma actin specifically localizes to Z-discs in striated muscle cells.
[src:actin/actg1] During development of myocytes, gamma actin is thought to play a role in the organization and assembly of developing sarcomeres, evidenced in part by its early colocalization with alpha-actinin.
[src:actin/actg1] Gamma-actin is eventually replaced by sarcomeric alpha-actin isoforms, with low levels of gamma-actin persisting in adult myocytes which associate with Z-disc and costamere domains.
[src:actin/actg1] Insights into the function of gamma-actin in muscle have come from studies employing transgenesis.
[src:actin/actg1] An autosomal dominant mutation in *ACTG1* in the DFNA20/26 locus at 17q25-qter was identified in patients with hearing loss.
[src:actin/actg1] A Thr278Ile mutation was identified in helix 9 of gamma-actin protein, which is predicted to alter protein structure.
[src:actin/actg1] This study identified the first disease causing mutation in gamma-actin and underlies the importance of gamma-actin as structural elements of the inner ear hair cells.
[src:actin/actg1] Since then, other *ACTG1* mutations have been linked to nonsyndromic hearing loss, including Met305Thr.
[src:actin/actg1] Differential expression of *ACTG1* mRNA was also identified in patients with Sporadic Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis, a devastating disease with unknown causality, using a sophisticated bioinformatics approach employing Affymetrix long-oligonucleotide BaFL methods.
[src:actin/actg1] Single nucleotide polymorphisms in *ACTG1* have been associated with vincristine toxicity, which is part of the standard treatment regimen for childhood acute lymphoblastic leukemia.
[src:actin/actg1] Neurotoxicity was more frequent in patients that were *ACTG1* Gly310Ala mutation carriers, suggesting that this may play a role in patient outcomes from vincristine treatment.
[src:actin/actin-p01] An actin protein is the monomeric subunit of two types of filaments in cells: microfilaments, one of the three major components of the cytoskeleton, and thin filaments, part of the contractile apparatus in muscle cells.
[src:actin/actin-p01] It can be present as either a free monomer called **G-actin** (globular) or as part of a linear polymer microfilament called **F-actin** (filamentous), both of which are essential for such important cellular functions as the mobility and contraction of cells during cell division.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin participates in many important cellular processes, including muscle contraction, cell motility, cell division and cytokinesis, vesicle and organelle movement, cell signaling, and the establishment and maintenance of cell junctions and cell shape.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Many of these processes are mediated by extensive and intimate interactions of actin with cellular membranes.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In vertebrates, three main groups of actin isoforms, alpha, beta, and gamma have been identified.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The alpha actins, found in muscle tissues, are a major constituent of the contractile apparatus.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The beta and gamma actins coexist in most cell types as components of the cytoskeleton, and as mediators of internal cell motility.
[src:actin/actin-p01] It is believed that the diverse range of structures formed by actin enabling it to fulfill such a large range of functions is regulated through the binding of tropomyosin along the filaments.
[src:actin/actin-p01] A cell's ability to dynamically form microfilaments provides the scaffolding that allows it to rapidly remodel itself in response to its environment or to the organism's internal signals, for example, to increase cell membrane absorption or increase cell adhesion in order to form cell tissue.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Other enzymes or organelles such as cilia can be anchored to this scaffolding in order to control the deformation of the external cell membrane, which allows endocytosis and cytokinesis.
[src:actin/actin-p01] It can also produce movement either by itself or with the help of molecular motors.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin therefore contributes to processes such as the intracellular transport of vesicles and organelles as well as muscular contraction and cellular migration.
[src:actin/actin-p01] It therefore plays an important role in embryogenesis, the healing of wounds, and the invasivity of cancer cells.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The evolutionary origin of actin can be traced to prokaryotic cells, which have equivalent proteins.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin homologs from prokaryotes and archaea polymerize into different helical or linear filaments consisting of one or multiple strands.
[src:actin/actin-p01] However the in-strand contacts and nucleotide binding sites are preserved in prokaryotes and in archaea.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Lastly, actin plays an important role in the control of gene expression.
[src:actin/actin-p01] A large number of illnesses and diseases are caused by mutations in alleles of the genes that regulate the production of actin or of its associated proteins.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The production of actin is also key to the process of infection by some pathogenic microorganisms.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Mutations in the different genes that regulate actin production in humans can cause muscular diseases, variations in the size and function of the heart as well as deafness.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The make-up of the cytoskeleton is also related to the pathogenicity of intracellular bacteria and viruses, particularly in the processes related to evading the actions of the immune system.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin's primary role in the cell is to form linear polymers called microfilaments that serve various functions in the cell's structure, trafficking networks, migration, and replication.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The multifaceted role of actin relies on a few of the microfilaments' properties: First, the formation of actin filaments is reversible, and their function often involves undergoing rapid polymerization and depolymerization.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Second, microfilaments are polarized – i.e. the two ends of a filament are distinct from one another.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Third, actin filaments can bind to many other proteins, which together help modify and organize microfilaments for their diverse functions.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin is extremely abundant in most cells, comprising 1–5% of the total protein mass of most cells, and 10% of muscle cells.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The actin protein is found in both the cytoplasm and the cell nucleus.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Its location is regulated by cell membrane signal transduction pathways that integrate the stimuli that a cell receives stimulating the restructuring of the actin networks in response.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The role of actin as a regulator of chemical processes in the cell cytoplasm was proposed.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The cytoplasm is viscous, crowded, and heterogeneous, a dynamic complex, a gel-like substance that restricts free diffusion but is capable of managing a myriad of reactions at any moment.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The high capacity of the cytoplasm to perform complex chemical reactions can be explained by a two-phase system of organization, in which catalytic complexes are immobilized in the elastic solid phase (cytomatrix), thereby overcoming spatial hindrances and crowding .
[src:actin/actin-p01] Nutrients and substrates can be delivered by liquid-phase (cytosol) flux, and the motor protein actin provides the driving force for cytomatrix mechanics.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Approximately 150 actin-binding and regulatory proteins fine-tune metabolic processes in the cytoplasm, thereby overcoming cytoplasmic viscosity.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The energy source for actin dynamics in normal physiological conditions is mitochondria.
[src:actin/actin-p01] However, cancer cells, due to their high metabolic rate, require additional ATP, which can be supplied by glycolysis (the Warburg effect).
[src:actin/actin-p01] There are a number of different types of actin with slightly different structures and functions. α-actin is found exclusively in muscle fibres, while β- and γ-actin are found in other cells.
[src:actin/actin-p01] As the latter types have a high turnover rate the majority of them are found outside permanent structures.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin's cytoskeleton is key to the processes of endocytosis, cytokinesis, determination of cell polarity and morphogenesis in yeasts.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In addition to relying on actin, these processes involve 20 or 30 associated proteins, which all have a high degree of evolutionary conservation, along with many signalling molecules.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Together these elements allow a spatially and temporally modulated assembly that defines a cell's response to both internal and external stimuli.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Yeasts contain three main elements that are associated with actin: patches, cables, and rings.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Despite not being present for long, these structures are subject to a dynamic equilibrium due to continual polymerization and depolymerization.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Plant genome studies have revealed the existence of protein isovariants within the actin family of genes.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Within *Arabidopsis thaliana*, a model organism, there are ten types of actin, six profilins, and dozens of myosins.
[src:actin/actin-p01] This diversity is explained by the evolutionary necessity of possessing variants that slightly differ in their temporal and spatial expression.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The majority of these proteins were jointly expressed in the tissue analysed.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin networks are distributed throughout the cytoplasm of cells that have been cultivated *in vitro*.
[src:actin/actin-p01] There is a concentration of the network around the nucleus that is connected via spokes to the cellular cortex, this network is highly dynamic, with a continuous polymerization and depolymerization.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Even though the majority of plant cells have a cell wall that defines their morphology, their microfilaments can generate sufficient force to achieve a number of cellular activities, such as the cytoplasmic currents generated by the microfilaments and myosin.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin is also involved in the movement of organelles and in cellular morphogenesis, which involve cell division as well as the elongation and differentiation of the cell.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Nuclear actin was first noticed and described in 1977 by Clark and Merriam.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Authors describe a protein present in the nuclear fraction, obtained from *Xenopus laevis* oocytes, which shows the same features as skeletal muscle actin.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The actin sequence does not contain a nuclear localization signal.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The small size of actin (about 43 kDa) allows it to enter the nucleus by passive diffusion.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The import of actin into the nucleus (probably in a complex with cofilin) is facilitated by the import protein importin 9.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Low levels of actin in the nucleus seems to be important, because actin has two nuclear export signals (NES) in its sequence.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Microinjected actin is quickly removed from the nucleus to the cytoplasm.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin is exported at least in two ways, through exportin 1 and exportin 6.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Specific modifications, such as SUMOylation, allows for nuclear actin retention.
[src:actin/actin-p01] A mutation preventing SUMOylation causes rapid export of beta actin from the nucleus.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Nuclear actin exists mainly as a monomer, but can also form dynamic oligomers and short polymers.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Nuclear actin organization varies in different cell types.
[src:actin/actin-p01] For example, in *Xenopus* oocytes (with higher nuclear actin level in comparison to somatic cells) actin forms filaments, which stabilize nucleus architecture.
[src:actin/actin-p01] These filaments can be observed under the microscope thanks to fluorophore-conjugated phalloidin staining.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In somatic cell nuclei, however, actin filaments cannot be observed using this technique.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The DNase I inhibition assay, the only test which allows the quantification of the polymerized actin directly in biological samples, has revealed that endogenous nuclear actin indeed occurs mainly in a monomeric form.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Precisely controlled level of actin in the cell nucleus, lower than in the cytoplasm, prevents the formation of filaments.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The polymerization is also reduced by the limited access to actin monomers, which are bound in complexes with ABPs, mainly cofilin.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Different isoforms of actin are present in the cell nucleus.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The level of actin isoforms may change in response to stimulation of cell growth or arrest of proliferation and transcriptional activity.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Research on nuclear actin is focused on isoform beta.
[src:actin/actin-p01] However the use of antibodies directed against different actin isoforms allows identifying not only the cytoplasmic beta in the cell nucleus, but also alpha- and gamma-actin in certain cell types.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The presence of different isoforms of actin may have a significant effect on its function in nuclear processes, as the level of individual isoforms can be controlled independently.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Functions of actin in the nucleus are associated with its ability to polymerize and interact with various ABPs and with structural elements of the nucleus.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Due to its ability to undergo conformational changes and interaction with many proteins, actin acts as a regulator of formation and activity of protein complexes such as transcriptional complex.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin is also involved in cell movement.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Several different types of protrusions mediated directly or indirectly by actin are involved in cell migration in different ways, with the most important ones being lamellipodia, filopodia, invadopodia and blebs.
[src:actin/actin-p01] A meshwork of actin filaments marks the forward edge of a moving cell, and the polymerization of new actin filaments pushes the cell membrane forward in protrusions called lamellipodia.
[src:actin/actin-p01] These membrane protrusions then attach to the substrate, forming structures known as focal adhesions that connect to the actin network.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Once attached, the rear of the cell body contracts squeezing its contents forward past the adhesion point.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Once the adhesion point has moved to the rear of the cell, the cell disassembles it, allowing the rear of the cell to move forward.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Filopodia are thin extensions of the plasma membrane that contain parallel bundles of actin filaments, in contrast to the branched actin structures of lamellipodia.
[src:actin/actin-p01] They serve an exploratory role, being used by cells to probe their environment.
[src:actin/actin-p01] While the presence of filopodia is linked to enhanced cell migration, they are not directly involved in cell body displacement.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Invadopodia are actin-driven membrane protrusions that help to degrade the extracellular matrix.
[src:actin/actin-p01] They are used by cancer cells for cell invasion, particularly to help them cross the basement membrane.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The matrix degradation takes place by transporting vesicles containing matrix-degrading proteins to the invadopodia where the proteins are released via exocytosis.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Blebs are spherical membrane protrusions that are involved in both apoptosis and cell movement.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The driving force behind bleb extension is hydrostatic pressure, rather than actin filament elongation which drives lamellipodia, filopodia and invadopodia extension.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Blebs are formed by actomyosin contraction, which causes the delamination of the plasma membrane from the actin cortex or a focal rupture of the actin cortex.
[src:actin/actin-p01] They are then stabilized via actin cortex reassembly and finally retracted via actomyosin contraction.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In migrating cells a front-rear polarity is established, with bleb formation restricted to the leading edge, allowing for directed movement.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In addition to the physical force generated by actin polymerization, microfilaments facilitate the movement of various intracellular components by serving as the roadway along which a family of motor proteins called myosins travel.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin plays a particularly prominent role in muscle cells, which consist largely of repeated bundles of actin and myosin II.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Each repeated unit – called a sarcomere – consists of two sets of oppositely oriented F-actin strands ("thin filaments"), interlaced with bundles of myosin ("thick filaments").
[src:actin/actin-p01] The two sets of actin strands are oriented with their (+) ends embedded in either end of the sarcomere in delimiting structures called Z-disks.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The myosin fibrils are in the middle between the sets of actin filaments, with strands facing in both directions.
[src:actin/actin-p01] When the muscle contracts, the myosin threads move along the actin filaments towards the (+) end, pulling the ends of the sarcomere together and shortening it by around 70% of its length.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In order to move along the actin thread, myosin must hydrolyze ATP; thus ATP serves as the energy source for muscle contraction.
[src:actin/actin-p01] At times of rest, the proteins tropomyosin and troponin bind to the actin filaments, preventing the attachment of myosin.
[src:actin/actin-p01] When an activation signal (i.e. an action potential) arrives at the muscle fiber, it triggers the release of Ca2+ from the sarcoplasmic reticulum into the cytosol.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The resulting spike in cytosolic calcium rapidly releases tropomyosin and troponin from the actin thread, allowing myosin to bind, and muscle contraction to begin.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In the final stages of cell division, many cells form a ring of actin at the cell's midpoint.
[src:actin/actin-p01] This ring, aptly called the "contractile ring", uses a similar mechanism as muscle fibers where myosin II pulls along the actin ring, causing it to contract.
[src:actin/actin-p01] This contraction cleaves the parent cell into two, completing cytokinesis.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The contractile ring is composed of actin, myosin, anillin, and α-actinin.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In the fission yeast *Schizosaccharomyces pombe*, actin is actively formed in the constricting ring with the participation of Arp3, the formin Cdc12, profilin, and WASp, along with preformed microfilaments.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Once the ring has been constructed the structure is maintained by a continual assembly and disassembly that, aided by the Arp2/3 complex and formins, is key to one of the central processes of cytokinesis.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin-myosin pairs can also participate in the trafficking of various membrane vesicles and organelles within the cell.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Myosin V is activated by binding to various cargo receptors on organelles, and then moves along an actin filament towards the (+) end, pulling its cargo along with it.
[src:actin/actin-p01] These nonconventional myosins use ATP hydrolysis to transport cargo, such as vesicles and organelles, in a directed fashion much faster than diffusion.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Myosin V walks towards the barbed end of actin filaments, while myosin VI walks toward the pointed end.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Most actin filaments are arranged with the barbed end toward the cellular membrane and the pointed end toward the cellular interior.
[src:actin/actin-p01] This arrangement allows myosin V to be an effective motor for the export of cargos, and myosin VI to be an effective motor for import.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The traditional image of actin's function relates it to the maintenance of the cytoskeleton and, therefore, the organization and movement of organelles, as well as the determination of a cell's shape.
[src:actin/actin-p01] However, actin has a wider role in eukaryotic cell physiology, in addition to similar functions in prokaryotes.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Monomeric actin, or G-actin, has a globular structure consisting of two lobes separated by a deep cleft.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The bottom of the cleft represents the "ATPase fold", a structure conserved among ATP and GTP-binding proteins that binds to a magnesium ion and a molecule of ATP.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Binding of ATP or ADP is required to stabilize each actin monomer; without one of these molecules bound, actin quickly becomes denatured.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The X-ray crystallography model of actin that was produced by Kabsch from the striated muscle tissue of rabbits is the most commonly used in structural studies as it was the first to be purified.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The G-actin crystallized by Kabsch is approximately 67 x 40 x 37 Å in size, has a molecular mass of 41,785 Da and an estimated isoelectric point of 4.8.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Elzinga and co-workers first determined the complete peptide sequence for this type of actin in 1973, with later work by the same author adding further detail to the model.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Its N-terminus is highly acidic and starts with an acetyled aspartate in its amino group, while its C-terminus is alkaline and is formed by a phenylalanine preceded by a cysteine, which has a degree of functional importance.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Both extremes are in close proximity within the I-subdomain.
[src:actin/actin-p01] An anomalous *N*τ-methylhistidine is located at position 73.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The tertiary structure is formed by two domains known as the large and the small, which are separated by a cleft centred around the location of the bond with ATP-ADP+Pi.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Below this there is a deeper notch called a "groove".
[src:actin/actin-p01] In the native state, despite their names, both have a comparable depth.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The normal convention in topological studies means that a protein is shown with the biggest domain on the left-hand side and the smallest domain on the right-hand side.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In this position the smaller domain is in turn divided into two: subdomain I (lower position, residues 1–32, 70–144, and 338–374) and subdomain II (upper position, residues 33–69).
[src:actin/actin-p01] The larger domain is also divided in two: subdomain III (lower, residues 145–180 and 270–337) and subdomain IV (higher, residues 181–269).
[src:actin/actin-p01] The exposed areas of subdomains I and III are referred to as the "barbed" ends, while the exposed areas of domains II and IV are termed the "pointed" ends.
[src:actin/actin-p01] This nomenclature refers to the fact that, due to the small mass of subdomain II actin is polar; the importance of this will be discussed below in the discussion on assembly dynamics.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Some authors call the subdomains Ia, Ib, IIa, and IIb, respectively.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The most notable supersecondary structure is a five chain beta sheet that is composed of a β-meander and a β-α-β clockwise unit.
[src:actin/actin-p01] It is present in both domains suggesting that the protein arose from gene duplication.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Under various conditions, G-actin molecules polymerize into longer threads called "filamentous-" or "F-actin".
[src:actin/actin-p01] These F-actin threads are typically composed of two helical strands of actin wound around each other, forming a 7 to 9 nanometer wide helix that repeats every 72 nanometers (or every 14 G-actin subunits).
[src:actin/actin-p01] In F-actin threads, G-actin molecules are all oriented in the same direction.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The two ends of the F-actin thread are distinct from one another.
[src:actin/actin-p01] At one end – designated the (−) end – the ATP-binding cleft of the terminal actin molecule is facing outward.
[src:actin/actin-p01] At the opposite end – designated (+) – the ATP-binding cleft is buried in the filament, contacting the neighboring actin molecule.
[src:actin/actin-p01] As F-actin threads grow, new molecules tend to join at the (+) end of an existing F-actin strand.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Conversely, threads tend to shrink by shedding actin monomers from the strand's (−) end.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Some proteins, such as cofilin appear to increase the angle of turn, but again this could be interpreted as the establishment of different structural states.
[src:actin/actin-p01] These could be important in the polymerization process.
[src:actin/actin-p01] There is less agreement regarding measurements of the turn radius and filament thickness: while the first models assigned a length of 25 Å, current X-ray diffraction data, backed up by cryo-electron microscopy suggests a length of 23.7 Å.
[src:actin/actin-p01] These studies have shown the precise contact points between monomers.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Some are formed with units of the same chain, between the "barbed" end on one monomer and the "pointed" end of the next one.
[src:actin/actin-p01] While the monomers in adjacent chains make lateral contact through projections from subdomain IV, with the most important projections being those formed by the C-terminus and the hydrophobic link formed by three bodies involving residues 39–42, 201–203, and 286.
[src:actin/actin-p01] This model suggests that a filament is formed by monomers in a "sheet" formation, in which the subdomains turn about themselves, this form is also found in the bacterial actin homologue MreB.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The terms "pointed" and "barbed" referring to the two ends of the microfilaments derive from their appearance under transmission electron microscopy when samples are examined following a preparation technique called "decoration".
[src:actin/actin-p01] This method consists of the addition of myosin S1 fragments to tissue that has been fixed with tannic acid.
[src:actin/actin-p01] This myosin forms polar bonds with actin monomers, giving rise to a configuration that looks like arrows with feather fletchings along its shaft, where the shaft is the actin and the fletchings are the myosin.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Following this logic, the end of the microfilament that does not have any protruding myosin is called the point of the arrow (− end) and the other end is called the barbed end (+ end).
[src:actin/actin-p01] A S1 fragment is composed of the head and neck domains of myosin II.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Under physiological conditions, G-actin (the monomer form) is transformed to F-actin (the polymer form) by ATP, where the role of ATP is essential.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The helical F-actin filament found in muscles also contains a tropomyosin molecule, which is a 40 nanometre long protein that is wrapped around the F-actin helix.
[src:actin/actin-p01] During the resting phase the tropomyosin covers the actin's active sites so that the actin-myosin interaction cannot take place and produce muscular contraction.
[src:actin/actin-p01] There are other protein molecules bound to the tropomyosin thread, these are the troponins that have three polymers: troponin I, troponin T, and troponin C.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Unlike other polymers, such as DNA, whose constituent elements are bound together with covalent bonds, the monomers of actin filaments are assembled by weaker bonds.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The lateral bonds with neighbouring monomers resolve this anomaly, which in theory should weaken the structure as they can be broken by thermal agitation.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In addition, the weak bonds give the advantage that the filament ends can easily release or incorporate monomers.
[src:actin/actin-p01] This means that the filaments can be rapidly remodelled and can change cellular structure in response to an environmental stimulus.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Which, along with the biochemical mechanism by which it is brought about is known as the "assembly dynamic".
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin can spontaneously acquire a large part of its tertiary structure.
[src:actin/actin-p01] However, the way it acquires its fully functional form from its newly synthesized native form is special and almost unique in protein chemistry.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The reason for this special route could be the need to avoid the presence of incorrectly folded actin monomers, which could be toxic as they can act as inefficient polymerization terminators.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Nevertheless, it is key to establishing the stability of the cytoskeleton, and additionally, it is an essential process for coordinating the cell cycle.
[src:actin/actin-p01] CCT is required in order to ensure that folding takes place correctly.
[src:actin/actin-p01] CCT is a group II chaperonin, a large protein complex that assists in the folding of other proteins.
[src:actin/actin-p01] CCT is formed of a double ring of eight different subunits (hetero-octameric) and it differs from group I chaperonins like GroEL, which is found in Eubacteria and in eukaryotic organelles, as it does not require a co-chaperone to act as a lid over the central catalytic cavity.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Substrates bind to CCT through specific domains.
[src:actin/actin-p01] It was initially thought that it only bound with actin and tubulin, although recent immunoprecipitation studies have shown that it interacts with a large number of polypeptides, which possibly function as substrates.
[src:actin/actin-p01] It acts through ATP-dependent conformational changes that on occasion require several rounds of liberation and catalysis in order to complete a reaction.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In order to successfully complete their folding, both actin and tubulin need to interact with another protein called prefoldin, which is a heterohexameric complex (formed by six distinct subunits), in an interaction that is so specific that the molecules have coevolved.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin forms a complex with prefoldin while it is still being formed, when it is approximately 145 amino acids long, specifically those at the N-terminal.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Different recognition sub-units are used for actin or tubulin although there is some overlap.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In actin the subunits that bind with prefoldin are probably PFD3 and PFD4, which bind in two places one between residues 60–79 and the other between residues 170–198.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The actin is recognized, loaded, and delivered to the cytosolic chaperonin (CCT) in an open conformation by the inner end of prefoldin's "tentacles" (see the image and note).
[src:actin/actin-p01] The contact when actin is delivered is so brief that a tertiary complex is not formed, immediately freeing the prefoldin.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The CCT then causes actin's sequential folding by forming bonds with its subunits rather than simply enclosing it in its cavity.
[src:actin/actin-p01] This is why it possesses specific recognition areas in its apical β-domain.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The first stage in the folding consists of the recognition of residues 245–249.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Next, other determinants establish contact.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Both actin and tubulin bind to CCT in open conformations in the absence of ATP.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In actin's case, two subunits are bound during each conformational change, whereas for tubulin binding takes place with four subunits.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin has specific binding sequences, which interact with the δ and β-CCT subunits or with δ-CCT and ε-CCT.
[src:actin/actin-p01] After AMP-PNP is bound to CCT the substrates move within the chaperonin's cavity.
[src:actin/actin-p01] It also seems that in the case of actin, the CAP protein is required as a possible cofactor in actin's final folding states.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The exact manner by which this process is regulated is still not fully understood, but it is known that the protein PhLP3 (a protein similar to phosducin) inhibits its activity through the formation of a tertiary complex.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin is an ATPase, which means that it is an enzyme that hydrolyzes ATP.
[src:actin/actin-p01] This group of enzymes is characterised by their slow reaction rates.
[src:actin/actin-p01] It is known that this ATPase is "active", that is, its speed increases by some 40,000 times when the actin forms part of a filament.
[src:actin/actin-p01] A reference value for this rate of hydrolysis under ideal conditions is around 0.3 s−1.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Then, the Pi remains bound to the actin next to the ADP for a long time, until it is cooperatively liberated from the interior of the filament.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The exact molecular details of the catalytic mechanism are still not fully understood.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Although there is much debate on this issue, it seems certain that a "closed" conformation is required for the hydrolysis of ATP, and it is thought that the residues that are involved in the process move to the appropriate distance.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The glutamic acid Glu137 is one of the key residues, which is located in subdomain 1.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Its function is to bind the water molecule that produces a nucleophilic attack on the ATP's γ-phosphate bond, while the nucleotide is strongly bound to subdomains 3 and 4.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The slowness of the catalytic process is due to the large distance and skewed position of the water molecule in relation to the reactant.
[src:actin/actin-p01] It is highly likely that the conformational change produced by the rotation of the domains between actin's G and F forms moves the Glu137 closer allowing its hydrolysis.
[src:actin/actin-p01] This model suggests that the polymerization and ATPase's function would be decoupled straight away.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The "open" to "closed" transformation between G and F forms and its implications on the relative motion of several key residues and the formation of water wires have been characterized in molecular dynamics and QM/MM simulations.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin filaments are often rapidly assembled and disassembled, allowing them to generate force and support cell movement.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Assembly classically occurs in three steps.
[src:actin/actin-p01] First, the "nucleation phase", in which two to three G-actin molecules slowly join to form a small oligomer that will nucleate further growth.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Second, the "elongation phase", when the actin filament rapidly grows by the addition of many actin molecules to both ends.
[src:actin/actin-p01] As the filament grows, actin molecules are added to the (+) end of the filament around 10 times faster than to the (−) end, and so filaments tend to primarily grow at the (+) end.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Third, the "steady-state phase", where an equillibrium is reached as actin molecules join and leave the filament at the same rate, maintaining the filament's length.
[src:actin/actin-p01] While the filament's length remains constant in the steady-state phase, new molecules are constantly being added to the (+) end and falling off the (−) end, a phenomenon called "treadmilling" as a given actin molecule would appear to move along the strand.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In isolation, whether a filament will grow or shrink, and how quickly, are determined by the concentration of G-actin around the filament; however, in cells, the dynamics of actin filaments are heavily influenced by various actin-binding proteins.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The actin cytoskeleton *in vivo* is not exclusively composed of actin, other proteins are required for its formation, continuance, and function.
[src:actin/actin-p01] These proteins are called actin-binding proteins and they are involved in actin's polymerization, depolymerization, stability, and organisation.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The diversity of these proteins is such that actin is thought to be the protein that takes part in the greatest number of protein-protein interactions.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The nucleation of new actin filaments – the rate-limiting step in actin polymerization – is aided by actin-nucleating proteins such as formins (like formin-2) and the Arp2/3 complex.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Formins help to nucleate long actin filaments.
[src:actin/actin-p01] They bind two free actin-ATP molecules, bringing them together.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Then as the filament begins to grow, formin moves along the (+) end of the growing filament, all the while recruiting actin-binding proteins that promote filament growth, and excluding capping proteins that would block filament extension.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Branches in actin filaments are typically nucleated by the Arp2/3 complex in concert with nucleation promoting factors.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Nucleation promoting factors bind two free G-actin molecules, then recruit and activate the Arp2/3 complex.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The activated Arp2/3 complex attaches to an existing actin filament, and uses the two bound G-actin molecules to nucleate a new actin filament branching off of the old one at a 70° angle.
[src:actin/actin-p01] As filaments grow, the pool of available G-actin molecules is managed by G-actin-binding proteins such as profilin and thymosin β-4.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Profilin ensures a supply of available actin-ATP by binding to ADP-bound G-actin and promoting the exchange of ADP for ATP.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Profilin's binding to the actin molecule physically blocks its addition to a filament's (−) end, but permits it to join the (+) end.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Once the actin-ATP has joined the filament, profilin releases it.
[src:actin/actin-p01] As formins promote the nucleation and extension of new actin filaments, they recruit profilin to the area, increasing the local concentration of actin-ATP to boost filament growth.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In contrast, thymosin β-4 binds and sequesters actin-ATP, preventing it from joining a microfilament.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Once an actin fiber is established, the dynamics of its growth or collapse are influenced by numerous proteins.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Existing strands can be interrupted by filament cleaving proteins, such as cofilin and gelsolin.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Cofilin binds along two actin-ADP molecules in a filament, forcing a movement that destabilizes the filament and causes it to break.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Gelsolin inserts itself between actin molecules in a filament, disrupting the filament.
[src:actin/actin-p01] After the filament breaks, gelsolin remains attached to the new (+) end, preventing it from growing, thus forcing its disassembly.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Other proteins bind to the ends of actin filaments, stabilizing them.
[src:actin/actin-p01] These are called "capping proteins" and include CapZ and tropomodulin.
[src:actin/actin-p01] CapZ binds the (+) end of a filament, preventing further addition or loss of actin from that end.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Tropomodulin binds to a filament's (−) end, again preventing addition or loss of molecule's at that end.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Tropomodulin is typically found in cells that require extremely stable actin filaments, such as those in muscle and red blood cells.
[src:actin/actin-p01] These actin binding proteins are typically regulated by various cellular signals to control actin assembly dynamics in different cellular locations.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Formins, for example, are typically folded in an inactive conformation until they're activated by the binding of the small GTPase Rho.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Actin branching at the cell membrane is important for cell movement, and so the plasma membrane lipid PIP2 activates the nucleation promoting factor WASp and inhibits CapZ.
[src:actin/actin-p01] WASp is also activated by the small GTPase Cdc42, while another nucleation promoting factor WAVE is activated by the GTPase Rac1.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Although most yeasts have only a single actin gene, higher eukaryotes, in general, express several isoforms of actin encoded by a family of related genes.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Mammals have at least six actin isoforms coded by separate genes, which are divided into three classes – alpha, beta, and gamma – according to their isoelectric points.
[src:actin/actin-p01] In general, alpha actins are found in muscle (α-skeletal, α-aortic smooth, α-cardiac), whereas beta and gamma isoforms are prominent in non-muscle cells (β-cytoplasmic, γ1-cytoplasmic, γ2-enteric smooth).
[src:actin/actin-p01] Although the amino acid sequences and *in vitro* properties of the isoforms are highly similar, these isoforms cannot completely substitute for one another *in vivo*.
[src:actin/actin-p01] Plants contains more than 60 actin genes and pseudogenes.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The typical actin gene has an approximately 100-nucleotide 5' UTR, a 1200-nucleotide translated region, and a 200-nucleotide 3' UTR.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The majority of actin genes are interrupted by introns, with up to six introns in any of 19 well-characterised locations.
[src:actin/actin-p01] The high conservation of the family makes actin the favoured model for studies comparing the introns-early and introns-late models of intron evolution.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Actin and closely related proteins are present in all organisms, suggesting the common ancestor of all life on Earth had actin.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Actin is one of the most conserved proteins throughout the evolution of eukaryotes.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The sequences of actin proteins from animals and amoebae are 80% identical despite being separated by approximately one billion years of evolution.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Many unicellular eukaryotes have a single actin gene, while multicellular eukaryotes often have several closely related genes that serve specialized functions.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Humans have six; plants have 10 or more.
[src:actin/actin-p02] In addition to actin, eukaryotes have a large family of actin-related proteins, or "Arps", that share a common ancestor with actin and are called Arp1–Arp11, with Arp1 the most closely related to actin, and Arp11 the least.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Bacteria encode three types of actin: MreB influences cell shape, FtsA cell division, and ParM separation of large plasmids.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Some archaea have a bacteria-like MreB gene, while others have an actin gene that more closely resembles eukaryote actin.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The eukaryotic cytoskeleton of organisms among all taxonomic groups have similar components to actin and tubulin.
[src:actin/actin-p02] For example, the protein that is coded by the *ACTG2* gene in humans is completely equivalent to the homologues present in rats and mice, even though at a nucleotide level the similarity decreases to 92%.
[src:actin/actin-p02] However, there are major differences with the equivalents in prokaryotes (FtsZ and MreB), where the similarity between nucleotide sequences is between 40 and 50% among different bacteria and archaea species.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Some authors suggest that the ancestral protein that gave rise to the model eukaryotic actin resembles the proteins present in modern bacterial cytoskeletons.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Some authors point out that the behaviour of actin, tubulin, and histone, a protein involved in the stabilization and regulation of DNA, are similar in their ability to bind nucleotides and in their ability of take advantage of Brownian motion.
[src:actin/actin-p02] It has also been suggested that they all have a common ancestor.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Therefore, evolutionary processes resulted in the diversification of ancestral proteins into the varieties present today, conserving, among others, actins as efficient molecules that were able to tackle essential ancestral biological processes, such as endocytosis.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The Arp2/3 complex is widely found in all eukaryotic organisms.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The bacterial cytoskeleton contains proteins that are highly similar to actin monomers and polymers.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The bacterial protein MreB polymerizes into thin non-helical filaments and occasionally into helical structures similar to F-actin.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Furthermore, its crystalline structure is very similar to that of G-actin (in terms of its three-dimensional conformation), there are even similarities between the MreB protofilaments and F-actin.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The bacterial cytoskeleton also contains the FtsZ proteins, which are similar to tubulin.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Bacteria therefore possess a cytoskeleton with homologous elements to actin (for example, MreB, AlfA, ParM, FtsA, and MamK), even though the amino acid sequence of these proteins diverges from that present in animal cells.
[src:actin/actin-p02] However, such proteins have a high degree of structural similarity to eukaryotic actin.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The highly dynamic microfilaments formed by the aggregation of MreB and ParM are essential to cell viability and they are involved in cell morphogenesis, chromosome segregation, and cell polarity.
[src:actin/actin-p02] ParM is an actin homologue that is coded in a plasmid and it is involved in the regulation of plasmid DNA.
[src:actin/actin-p02] ParMs from different bacterial plasmids can form astonishingly diverse helical structures comprising two or four strands to maintain faithful plasmid inheritance.
[src:actin/actin-p02] In archaea the homologue Ta0583 is even more similar to the eukaryotic actins.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The majority of mammals possess six different actin genes.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Of these, two code for the cytoskeleton (*ACTB* and *ACTG1*) while the other four are involved in skeletal striated muscle (*ACTA1*), smooth muscle tissue (*ACTA2*), intestinal muscles (*ACTG2*) and cardiac muscle (*ACTC1*).
[src:actin/actin-p02] The actin in the cytoskeleton is involved in the pathogenic mechanisms of many infectious agents, including HIV.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The vast majority of the mutations that affect actin are point mutations that have a dominant effect, with the exception of six mutations involved in nemaline myopathy.
[src:actin/actin-p02] This is because in many cases the mutant of the actin monomer acts as a "cap" by preventing the elongation of F-actin.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The mutation alters the structure and function of skeletal muscles producing one of three forms of myopathy: type 3 nemaline myopathy, congenital myopathy with an excess of thin myofilaments (CM) and congenital myopathy with fibre type disproportion (CMFTD).
[src:actin/actin-p02] Mutations have also been found that produce core myopathies.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Although their phenotypes are similar, in addition to typical nemaline myopathy some specialists distinguish another type of myopathy called actinic nemaline myopathy.
[src:actin/actin-p02] In the former, clumps of actin form instead of the typical rods.
[src:actin/actin-p02] It is important to state that a patient can show more than one of these phenotypes in a biopsy.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The most common symptoms consist of a typical facial morphology (myopathic facies), muscular weakness, a delay in motor development and respiratory difficulties.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The course of the illness, its gravity, and the age at which it appears are all variable and overlapping forms of myopathy are also found.
[src:actin/actin-p02] A symptom of nemaline myopathy is that "nemaline rods" appear in differing places in type 1 muscle fibres.
[src:actin/actin-p02] These rods are non-pathognomonic structures that have a similar composition to the Z disks found in the sarcomere.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The pathogenesis of this myopathy is very varied.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Many mutations occur in the region of actin's indentation near to its nucleotide binding sites, while others occur in Domain 2, or in the areas where interaction occurs with associated proteins.
[src:actin/actin-p02] This goes some way to explain the great variety of clumps that form in these cases, such as Nemaline or Intranuclear Bodies or Zebra Bodies.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Changes in actin's folding occur in nemaline myopathy as well as changes in its aggregation and there are also changes in the expression of other associated proteins.
[src:actin/actin-p02] In some variants where intranuclear bodies are found the changes in the folding masks the nucleus's protein exportation signal so that the accumulation of actin's mutated form occurs in the cell nucleus.
[src:actin/actin-p02] On the other hand, it appears that mutations to *ACTA1* that give rise to a CFTDM have a greater effect on sarcomeric function than on its structure.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Recent investigations have tried to understand this apparent paradox, which suggests there is no clear correlation between the number of rods and muscular weakness.
[src:actin/actin-p02] It appears that some mutations are able to induce a greater apoptosis rate in type II muscular fibres.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The *ACTC1* gene codes for the α-actin isoform present in heart muscle.
[src:actin/actin-p02] It was first sequenced by Hamada and co-workers in 1982, when it was found that it is interrupted by five introns.
[src:actin/actin-p02] It was the first of the six genes where alleles were found that were implicated in pathological processes.
[src:actin/actin-p02] A number of structural disorders associated with point mutations of this gene have been described that cause malfunctioning of the heart, such as Type 1R dilated cardiomyopathy and Type 11 hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Certain defects of the atrial septum have been described recently that could also be related to these mutations.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Two cases of dilated cardiomyopathy have been studied involving a substitution of highly conserved amino acids belonging to the protein domains that bind and intersperse with the Z discs.
[src:actin/actin-p02] This has led to the theory that the dilation is produced by a defect in the transmission of contractile force in the myocytes.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The mutations in ACTC1 are responsible for at least 5% of hypertrophic cardiomyopathies.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Recent studies have discovered ACTC1 mutations that are implicated in two other pathological processes: Infantile idiopathic restrictive cardiomyopathy, and noncompaction of the left ventricular myocardium.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The *ACTG1* locus codes for the cytosolic γ-actin protein that is responsible for the formation of cytoskeletal microfilaments.
[src:actin/actin-p02] It contains six exons, giving rise to 22 different mRNAs, which produce four complete isoforms whose form of expression is probably dependent on the type of tissue they are found in.
[src:actin/actin-p02] It also has two different DNA promoters.
[src:actin/actin-p02] It has been noted that the sequences translated from this locus and from that of β-actin are very similar to the predicted ones, suggesting a common ancestral sequence that suffered duplication and genetic conversion.
[src:actin/actin-p02] In terms of pathology, it has been associated with processes such as amyloidosis, retinitis pigmentosa, infection mechanisms, kidney diseases, and various types of congenital hearing loss.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Six autosomal-dominant point mutations in the sequence have been found to cause various types of hearing loss, particularly sensorineural hearing loss linked to the DFNA 20/26 locus.
[src:actin/actin-p02] It seems that they affect the stereocilia of the ciliated cells present in the inner ear's Organ of Corti. β-actin is the most abundant protein found in human tissue, but it is not very abundant in ciliated cells, which explains the location of the pathology.
[src:actin/actin-p02] On the other hand, it appears that the majority of these mutations affect the areas involved in linking with other proteins, particularly actomyosin.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Some experiments have suggested that the pathological mechanism for this type of hearing loss relates to the F-actin in the mutations being more sensitive to cofilin than normal.
[src:actin/actin-p02] However, although there is no record of any case, it is known that γ-actin is also expressed in skeletal muscles, and although it is present in small quantities, model organisms have shown that its absence can give rise to myopathies.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Some infectious agents use actin, especially cytoplasmic actin, in their life cycle.
[src:actin/actin-p02] In addition to the previously cited example, actin polymerization is stimulated in the initial steps of the internalization of some viruses, notably HIV, by, for example, inactivating the cofilin complex.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The role that actin plays in the invasion process of cancer cells has still not been determined.
[src:actin/actin-p02] In conditions of high lipoperoxidation, actin has been shown to be post-translationally modified by the lipoperoxidation product 4-hydroxynonenal (4-HNE).
[src:actin/actin-p02] This modification prevents the remodelling of the actin cytoskeleton, which is essential for cell motility.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Additionally, another functional protein, coronin-1A, which stabilizes F-actin filaments, is also covalently modified by 4-HNE.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Actin is used in scientific and technological laboratories as a track for molecular motors such as myosin (either in muscle tissue or outside it) and as a necessary component for cellular functioning.
[src:actin/actin-p02] It can also be used as a diagnostic tool, as several of its anomalous variants are related to the appearance of specific pathologies.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The use of actin as an internal control is based on the assumption that its expression is practically constant and independent of experimental conditions.
[src:actin/actin-p02] By comparing the expression of the gene of interest to that of the actin, it is possible to obtain a relative quantity that can be compared between different experiments, whenever the expression of the latter is constant.
[src:actin/actin-p02] It is worth pointing out that actin does not always have the desired stability in its gene expression.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Actin was first observed experimentally in 1887 by W.D.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Halliburton, who extracted a protein from muscle that 'coagulated' preparations of myosin that he called "myosin-ferment".
[src:actin/actin-p02] However, Halliburton was unable to further refine his findings, and the discovery of actin is credited instead to Brunó Ferenc Straub, a young biochemist working in Albert Szent-Györgyi's laboratory at the Institute of Medical Chemistry at the University of Szeged, Hungary.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Following up on the discovery of Ilona Banga & Szent-Györgyi in 1941 that the coagulation only occurs in some myosin extractions and was reversed upon the addition of ATP, Straub identified and purified actin from those myosin preparations that did coagulate.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Building on Banga's original extraction method, he developed a novel technique for extracting muscle protein that allowed him to isolate substantial amounts of relatively pure actin, published in 1942.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Straub's method is essentially the same as that used in laboratories today.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Since Straub's protein was necessary to activate the coagulation of myosin, it was dubbed *actin*.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Realizing that Banga's coagulating myosin preparations contained actin as well, Szent-Györgyi called the mixture of both proteins actomyosin.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The hostilities of World War II meant Szent-Gyorgyi was unable to publish his lab's work in Western scientific journals.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Actin therefore only became well known in the West in 1945, when their paper was published as a supplement to the *Acta Physiologica Scandinavica*.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Straub continued to work on actin, and in 1950 reported that actin contains bound ATP and that, during polymerization of the protein into microfilaments, the nucleotide is hydrolyzed to ADP and inorganic phosphate (which remain bound to the microfilament).
[src:actin/actin-p02] Straub suggested that the transformation of ATP-bound actin to ADP-bound actin played a role in muscular contraction.
[src:actin/actin-p02] In fact, this is true only in smooth muscle, and was not supported through experimentation until 2001.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The amino acid sequencing of actin was completed by M.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The crystal structure of G-actin was solved in 1990 by Kabsch and colleagues.
[src:actin/actin-p02] In the same year, a model for F-actin was proposed by Holmes and colleagues following experiments using co-crystallization with different proteins.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The procedure of co-crystallization with different proteins was used repeatedly during the following years, until in 2001 the isolated protein was crystallized along with ADP.
[src:actin/actin-p02] However, there is still no high-resolution X-ray structure of F-actin.
[src:actin/actin-p02] The crystallization of G-actin was possible due to the use of a rhodamine conjugate that impedes polymerization by blocking the amino acid cys-374.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Christine Oriol-Audit died in the same year that actin was first crystallized but she was the researcher that in 1977 first crystallized actin in the absence of Actin Binding Proteins (ABPs).
[src:actin/actin-p02] However, the resulting crystals were too small for the available technology of the time.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Although no high-resolution model of actin's filamentous form currently exists, in 2008 Sawaya's team were able to produce a more exact model of its structure based on multiple crystals of actin dimers that bind in different places.
[src:actin/actin-p02] This model has subsequently been further refined by Sawaya and Lorenz.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Other approaches such as the use of cryo-electron microscopy and synchrotron radiation have recently allowed increasing resolution and better understanding of the nature of the interactions and conformational changes implicated in the formation of actin filaments.
[src:actin/actin-p02] A number of natural toxins that interfere with actin's dynamics are widely used in research to study actin's role in biology.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Latrunculin – a toxin produced by sponges – binds to G-actin preventing it from joining microfilaments.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Cytochalasin D – produced by certain fungi – serves as a capping factor, binding to the (+) end of a filament and preventing further addition of actin molecules.
[src:actin/actin-p02] In contrast, the sponge toxin jasplakinolide promotes the nucleation of new actin filaments by binding and stabilizing pairs of actin molecules.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Phalloidin – from the "death cap" mushroom *Amanita phalloides* – binds to adjacent actin molecules within the F-actin filament, stabilizing the filament and preventing its depolymerization.
[src:actin/actin-p02] Phalloidin is often labelled with fluorescent dyes to visualize actin filaments by fluorescence microscopy.
